<script type='text/javascript'>
/* <![CDATA[ */
var VENTURES = {"THEME_URL":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/themes\/ventures","AJAX_URL":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-admin\/admin-ajax.php","WPP_NONCE":"25805ea2d1","LATEST_ARTICLES_PER_PAGE":"6","ENABLE_NARROW_TEASERS_CAROUSEL":"","RELATED_POSTS":[{"id":"214476","title":"Fetish Justice: Ogun state police to work with herbalists to catch kidnappers","image":{"src":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Babalawo-320x226.jpg","srcset":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Babalawo-320x226.jpg 320w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Babalawo-640x453.jpg 640w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Babalawo-768x543.jpg 768w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Babalawo-1536x1086.jpg 1536w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Babalawo-3072x2172.jpg 3072w","data-original-width":3510,"sizes":"100vw","class":"thumb"},"image_alt":"","credit_html":"<header class=\"credit\"><\/header>","class":["type-post","no-credit"],"author":{"name":"Abdulmalik Fahd","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/author\/abdulmalik\/"},"category_label":{"title":"Policy","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/category\/policy\/"},"date":"November 28, 2016","content":"<p>Unconventional, unorthodox and yet adaptive? Chances are that the efforts of the Nigeria Police to partner with herbalists to counter cases of ritual killings, body part trafficking and kidnapping have been met with shock and then, skepticism. Well, the Ogun state, Commissioner of Police (CP), <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nigerianbulletin.com\/threads\/nigeria-police-partners-herbalists-to-curb-\u2018human-part-business\u2019-in-ogun.227646\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.nigerianbulletin.com\/threads\/nigeria-police-partners-herbalists-to-curb-\u2018human-part-business\u2019-in-ogun.227646\/', 'Ahmed Iliyasu');\">Ahmed Iliyasu<\/a>, has called on traditional medicine practitioners, to assist the police with useful information.<\/p>\n<p>This is not the first time similar partnerships have been established to improve intelligence gathering and service delivery \u2013 they have partnered with <a href=\"http:\/\/www.thisdaylive.com\/index.php\/2016\/07\/02\/police-partners-intel-airtel-to-improve-operations\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.thisdaylive.com\/index.php\/2016\/07\/02\/police-partners-intel-airtel-to-improve-operations\/', 'network providers');\">network providers<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/techloy.com\/2015\/11\/06\/olx-partnership-with-nigeria-police-yield-results-two-suspected-scammers-arrested\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/techloy.com\/2015\/11\/06\/olx-partnership-with-nigeria-police-yield-results-two-suspected-scammers-arrested\/', 'online service');\">online service<\/a> vendors, and even <a href=\"http:\/\/www.vanguardngr.com\/2016\/03\/nigeria-police-partners-binggo-uac-subsidiary-k-9-dogs\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.vanguardngr.com\/2016\/03\/nigeria-police-partners-binggo-uac-subsidiary-k-9-dogs\/', 'dog food');\">dog food<\/a> providers but no one saw the relationship between the police and herbalists happening.<\/p>\n<p>The CP made this call at a workshop organised by the Police Community Relations Committee (PCRC), for alternative medicine practitioners in the Ogun state. \u201cHelp us to make the state free of kidnapping, cultism and dealings in human parts. Assess your clients to ascertain the genuineness and legality of the help they seek from you,\u201d he implored the participants of the workshop.<\/p>\n<p>The police in Nigeria has been plagued by public distrust as the uniform is viewed as a symbol of corruption and graft, inefficiency and brutality. \u201cCheckpoint bribery\u201d is still a common occurrence between the police and commuters, and it is not unusual for armed gangs to have better relationships with officers than citizens.<\/p>\n<p>The police have even tried to address the increasing cases of brutality and torture against members of the public, by setting up the <a href=\"http:\/\/npf.gov.ng\/complaint\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/npf.gov.ng\/complaint\/', 'Complaint Response Unit');\">Complaint Response Unit<\/a> (CRU) to monitor the conduct of its personnel, yet there are thousands of unreported cases against the police.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Well, who are the herbalists we\u2019re talking about?<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>In the position of the African traditional belief system and in Nigeria in particular, there are two groups that are recognised in relation to the \u201cherbalists\u201d of discussion.<\/p>\n<p>The Witches and Wizards Association of Nigeria (WITZAN) and the National Association of Nigerian Traditional Medicine Practitioners (NANTMP) \u2013 the former are concerned with the mystic and regulation of the occult and seen in the same circles as religion while the latter involve what some term as alchemy or a thorough knowledge of plants and their uses especially healthwise.<\/p>\n<p>It is believed that the police intend to work with the latter of the groups, as \u201cherbalists\u201d are well aware of activities that have led to kidnapping and related vices as well as catering a diverse clientele with different needs \u2013 but there\u2019s just a little bone of contention: traditional practitioners do not consider themselves to be <a href=\"http:\/\/tribuneonlineng.com\/traditional-medicine-practitioners-not-herbalist-practitioners\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/tribuneonlineng.com\/traditional-medicine-practitioners-not-herbalist-practitioners\/', 'herbalists');\">herbalists<\/a> \u2013 so who is the police working with?<\/p>\n<p>Well, one does not expect the Nigerian police to seek spiritual \u201cfortification\u201d from the herbalists, rather, establishing a network that is centred on access to information as the police is guided by intelligence.<\/p>\n<p>Ogun state, where the CP made the call has been burdened with reports of human trafficking, money rituals, and the lot, but so have other states in Nigeria, so, is the call to work together aimed at just this state alone or is there an intention to take it nationwide?<\/p>\n<p>Elsewhere on the African continent, partnerships with \u201cherbalists\u201d have been established &#8211; \u00a0Blade Nzimande, South Africa\u2019s Minister of Higher Education and Training, announced plans to have <a href=\"http:\/\/pulse.ng\/gist\/moving-up-sa-minister-to-introduce-bsc-in-witchcraft-into-education-system-id5494349.html\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/pulse.ng\/gist\/moving-up-sa-minister-to-introduce-bsc-in-witchcraft-into-education-system-id5494349.html', 'witchcraft');\">witchcraft<\/a> included in the curriculum from 2018; President Paul Biya\u00a0of Cameroon, gave approval for the use of<u><a href=\"http:\/\/pulse.ng\/gist\/boko-haram-cameroon-government-gives-witches-wizards-permission-to-fight-insurgents-id4644539.html\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/pulse.ng\/gist\/boko-haram-cameroon-government-gives-witches-wizards-permission-to-fight-insurgents-id4644539.html', '\u00a0witches and wizards');\">\u00a0witches and wizards<\/a><\/u> to fight Boko Haram insurgents.<\/p>\n<!-- Facebook Comments Plugin for WordPress: http:\/\/peadig.com\/wordpress-plugins\/facebook-comments\/ --><h3>Comments<\/h3><div class=\"fb-comments\" data-href=\"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/fetish-justice-police-herbalists-catch-kidnappers\/\" data-numposts=\"5\" data-width=\"100%\" data-colorscheme=\"light\"><\/div>","permalink":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/fetish-justice-police-herbalists-catch-kidnappers\/","short_url":"http:\/\/vnt.rs\/36l2p","share_links":[{"title":"Twitter","slug":"twitter","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?text=Fetish%20Justice%3A%20Ogun%20state%20police%20to%20work%20with%20herbalists%20to%20catch%20kidnappers%20-%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2F36l2p"},{"title":"Email","slug":"email","target_attr":"","url":"mailto:?subject=Fetish%20Justice%3A%20Ogun%20state%20police%20to%20work%20with%20herbalists%20to%20catch%20kidnappers&body=VENTURES%20AFRICA%3A%20Fetish%20Justice%3A%20Ogun%20state%20police%20to%20work%20with%20herbalists%20to%20catch%20kidnappers%20%0A%0ARead%20more%3A%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2F36l2p"},{"title":"Google+","slug":"googleplus","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/plus.google.com\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2F36l2p"},{"title":"LinkedIn","slug":"linkedin","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/cws\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2F36l2p"},{"title":"Facebook","slug":"facebook","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2F36l2p"}]},{"id":"214473","title":"EFCC arraigns man for forging FCMB investment certificate","image":{"src":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/EFCC-320x224.jpg","srcset":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/EFCC-320x224.jpg 320w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/EFCC-640x448.jpg 640w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/EFCC-768x538.jpg 768w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/EFCC-1536x1075.jpg 1536w","data-original-width":2000,"sizes":"100vw","class":"thumb"},"image_alt":"","credit_html":"<header class=\"credit\"><span>Photograph \u2014 Endemic Corruption and Unacceptable index in Nigeria <\/span><\/header>","class":["type-post","has-credit"],"author":{"name":"Adebola Adeniyi","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/author\/adebolaadeniyi\/"},"category_label":{"title":"Policy","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/category\/policy\/"},"date":"November 28, 2016","content":"<p>On November 24, Nwachukwu Placidus was arraigned by the EFCC (Economic and Financial Crimes Commission). He was charged before Honourable Justice Ibrahim Bature Gafai of the Federal High Court, Awka in Anambra State, for having committed a crime that bothers on Fraud and Falsification of First City Monument Bank Certificate of Investment (FCMB).<\/p>\n<p>The accused person pleaded not guilty to the ten-count charge sanctioned against him by the EFCC. He was later granted bail after his counsel Barrister D.M. Ezeani asked on his behalf.<\/p>\n<p>Barrister S.M.H. Ibekwute, the prosecuting counsel boldly disagreed with the bail application and defended his argument on the fact that the accused person has a police record hanging around his neck, and as such might be difficult to catch and halt his trial.<\/p>\n<p>In 2003, EFCC was established in response to pressure from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Financial_Action_Task_Force_on_Money_Laundering\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Financial_Action_Task_Force_on_Money_Laundering', 'Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering');\">Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering<\/a>, which named Nigeria as one of 23 countries non-cooperative in the international community\u2019s effort to fight money laundering. EFCC investigates financial crimes such as advance fee fraud (419 fraud) and money laundering.<\/p>\n<p>According to section 467, of the <a href=\"http:\/\/thenationonlineng.net\/forgery-and-the-senate\/\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/thenationonlineng.net\/forgery-and-the-senate\/', 'criminal code');\">criminal code<\/a>, \u201cAny person who forges any document, writing, or seal, is guilty of an offense which, unless otherwise stated, is a felony, and he is liable, if no other punishment is provided, to imprisonment for three years.\u201d<\/p>\n<p>In the meantime, Justice Gafai, who was in charge of the case listened to the defendant\u2019s plea and granted him bail. The defendant was instructed to bring 2 sureties which must be a civil servant of grade level 14 and above and must be verified by both the Head of Service and the Court Registrar.<\/p>\n<p>Also, the Nigerian Police serves as the investigating officer or institution of the state, which role is to bring offenders before the law to answer the charge of forgery.<\/p>\n<p>The case has been postponed to January 25, 2017, for the commencement of trial.<\/p>\n<!-- Facebook Comments Plugin for WordPress: http:\/\/peadig.com\/wordpress-plugins\/facebook-comments\/ --><h3>Comments<\/h3><div class=\"fb-comments\" data-href=\"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/efcc-arraigns-man-for-forging-fcmb-investment-certificate\/\" data-numposts=\"5\" data-width=\"100%\" data-colorscheme=\"light\"><\/div>","permalink":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/efcc-arraigns-man-for-forging-fcmb-investment-certificate\/","short_url":"http:\/\/vnt.rs\/vlwdk","share_links":[{"title":"Twitter","slug":"twitter","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?text=EFCC%20arraigns%20man%20for%20forging%20FCMB%20investment%20certificate%20-%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fvlwdk"},{"title":"Email","slug":"email","target_attr":"","url":"mailto:?subject=EFCC%20arraigns%20man%20for%20forging%20FCMB%20investment%20certificate&body=VENTURES%20AFRICA%3A%20EFCC%20arraigns%20man%20for%20forging%20FCMB%20investment%20certificate%20%0A%0ARead%20more%3A%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fvlwdk"},{"title":"Google+","slug":"googleplus","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/plus.google.com\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fvlwdk"},{"title":"LinkedIn","slug":"linkedin","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/cws\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fvlwdk"},{"title":"Facebook","slug":"facebook","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fvlwdk"}]},{"id":"214422","title":"Closing the Bridge: Uganda shuts down low-cost for-profit private schools","image":{"src":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Bridge-International-Academy-320x213.jpg","srcset":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Bridge-International-Academy-320x213.jpg 320w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Bridge-International-Academy-640x427.jpg 640w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Bridge-International-Academy-768x512.jpg 768w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Bridge-International-Academy-1536x1024.jpg 1536w","data-original-width":3000,"sizes":"100vw","class":"thumb"},"image_alt":"","credit_html":"<header class=\"credit\"><\/header>","class":["type-post","no-credit"],"author":{"name":"Abdulmalik Fahd","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/author\/abdulmalik\/"},"category_label":{"title":"Policy","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/category\/policy\/"},"date":"November 28, 2016","content":"<p>The legal woes of Bridge International Academies (BIA) operating in Uganda have gotten worse as a high court in the country has ordered the closure of its 63 schools by December 8 2016, citing unsanitary learning conditions and unqualified teachers.<\/p>\n<p>The latest judgement puts the lives of\u00a0Bridge&#8217;s estimated 12,000 pupils and 800 staff in jeopardy, as claims to provide education at a cost of $5 &#8211; $6 (N2,350 \u2013 N2,820) have been <a href=\"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/as-long-as-african-governments-continue-neglecting-education-expensive-private-schools-will-thrive\/\">debunked<\/a> by several educational advocacy groups as well as the Ugandan Ministry of Education.<\/p>\n<p>Bridge, in response to the allegations, released a <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bridgeinternationalacademies.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Clarification-on-Bridge-Uganda-Press-Release-16.11.16-1.pdf\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'download', 'http:\/\/www.bridgeinternationalacademies.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Clarification-on-Bridge-Uganda-Press-Release-16.11.16-1.pdf');\">press statement<\/a> to address the allegations leveled against the institution, saying that the syllabus used was in line with the Ugandan curriculum.<\/p>\n<p>Critics allege that the education methods at Bridge are not transparent and that a standardised approach to learning is hazardous adding that education has nothing to do with standardisation, rather debating, thinking and discussion.<\/p>\n<p>Moral decay has been another reason added to the list of why the Bridge academy should be shut down as the Ugandan Minister of Finance, Matia Kasaija, revealed that the recent closure of the schools was on the suspicion of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.monitor.co.ug\/News\/Education\/Bridge-academies-UMU-minister-Kasaija\/688336-3458598-pndxxhz\/index.html\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.monitor.co.ug\/News\/Education\/Bridge-academies-UMU-minister-Kasaija\/688336-3458598-pndxxhz\/index.html', 'pornography');\">pornography<\/a> being taught to students.<\/p>\n<p>The academy is an international school with operations in Kenya, India, Uganda and Nigeria. However, its expansion was halted in Uganda earlier in the year, when the education ministry suspended the expansion of the schools over poor infrastructure, issues with teachers and questionable curriculum.<\/p>\n<p>In a related development, teachers in Kenya want the government to also ban the chain of low-cost private primary and nursery schools as Wilson Sossion, secretary-general of the Kenya National Union of Teachers, said that the union would release a report criticizing Bridge in December.<\/p>\n<p>Bridge International Academy, was founded by an American couple, Shannon May and Joel Kimmelman, in 2008 in Nairobi, Kenya. Targeting low-income households that cannot afford to send their children to expensive private schools, but are dissatisfied with the public school system; the company started working in Uganda in 2015 after opening 405 schools in Kenya and uses an \u2018academy-in-a-box\u2019 model in which teachers read lessons from a tablet computer.<\/p>\n<!-- Facebook Comments Plugin for WordPress: http:\/\/peadig.com\/wordpress-plugins\/facebook-comments\/ --><h3>Comments<\/h3><div class=\"fb-comments\" data-href=\"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/closing-bridge-uganda-shuts-schools\/\" data-numposts=\"5\" data-width=\"100%\" data-colorscheme=\"light\"><\/div>","permalink":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/closing-bridge-uganda-shuts-schools\/","short_url":"http:\/\/vnt.rs\/qhn4c","share_links":[{"title":"Twitter","slug":"twitter","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?text=Closing%20the%20Bridge%3A%20Uganda%20shuts%20down%20low-cost%20for-profit%20private%20schools%20-%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fqhn4c"},{"title":"Email","slug":"email","target_attr":"","url":"mailto:?subject=Closing%20the%20Bridge%3A%20Uganda%20shuts%20down%20low-cost%20for-profit%20private%20schools&body=VENTURES%20AFRICA%3A%20Closing%20the%20Bridge%3A%20Uganda%20shuts%20down%20low-cost%20for-profit%20private%20schools%20%0A%0ARead%20more%3A%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fqhn4c"},{"title":"Google+","slug":"googleplus","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/plus.google.com\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fqhn4c"},{"title":"LinkedIn","slug":"linkedin","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/cws\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fqhn4c"},{"title":"Facebook","slug":"facebook","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fqhn4c"}]},{"id":"214415","title":"How armed militia groups are fueling genocide in the Democratic Republic of Congo","image":{"src":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/congo-320x185.jpeg","srcset":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/congo-320x185.jpeg 320w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/congo-640x370.jpeg 640w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/congo-768x444.jpeg 768w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/congo-1536x887.jpeg 1536w","data-original-width":1920,"sizes":"100vw","class":"thumb"},"image_alt":"","credit_html":"<header class=\"credit\"><span>Photograph \u2014 Medium.com<\/span><\/header>","class":["type-post","has-credit"],"author":{"name":"Iroegbu Chinaemerem Oti","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/author\/chinemere-oti\/"},"category_label":{"title":"Policy","url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/category\/policy\/"},"date":"November 28, 2016","content":"<p>The Democratic Republic of Congo has been described as a turf where Africa\u2019s own World War took place, as <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-13286306\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-13286306', 'six African\u00a0countries');\">six African\u00a0countries<\/a> fought each other on its\u00a0soil from 1996 to 2003. This war started with the invasion of Congo by Rwanda and Uganda to uproot Hutus that had fled the Rwandan genocide because they feared that some of the warlords who had perpetrated the genocide had fled to Congo to find safe haven. Six million lives were lost during the war, their deaths were either caused by the\u00a0fighting, diseases or malnutrition, which equally plagued the country during the war.<\/p>\n<p>The civil war ended in 2003, but ever since then, the Democratic of Congo has experienced no form of peace, as tribal wars and political infighting, fueled by armed militias, still form a big part of the country&#8217;s unrest and insecurity. The eastern part of DRC has served as a bedrock for this ethnic violence.<\/p>\n<p>During the weekend, in the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.aljazeera.com\/news\/2016\/11\/dr-congo-militia-attack-kills-dozens-eastern-region-161128041438749.html\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.aljazeera.com\/news\/2016\/11\/dr-congo-militia-attack-kills-dozens-eastern-region-161128041438749.html', 'Eastern part of Congo');\">Eastern part of Congo<\/a>, at least 34 people were killed, 12 injured and a village razed down during an outburst of ethnic violence after Nande ethnic militia invaded a displaced persons&#8217; camp in the Hutu village of Luhanga.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;The militia was searching for members of the Hutu community and wreaked carnage before burning down the village entirely. The attackers were there for more than an hour,&#8221; said the Center for the Promotion of Peace, Democracy, and Human Rights (CEPADHO) a local rights group.<\/p>\n<p>The Hutus and Nande tribes have been at it for two decades\u2013two decades that have seen the rise of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.reuters.com\/article\/us-congodemocratic-violence-idUSKCN0VH1VL\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.reuters.com\/article\/us-congodemocratic-violence-idUSKCN0VH1VL', 'ethnic rivalry');\">ethnic rivalry<\/a> in DRC. Their reasons for disputes range from land disputes to one party accusing the other of supporting the Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda (FDLR)\u2013the Rwandan rebel group\u2013, etc. But this isn\u2019t the first time Hutus have been the edge of the sword.<\/p>\n<p>In 1994, a UN report accused the coalition of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-11456605\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-11456605', 'Rwandan\/Burundian\/Ugandan Army');\">Rwandan\/Burundian\/Ugandan Army<\/a> of indiscriminately killing Hutus who fled Rwandan in their bid to capture alleged warlords who they claimed escaped from Rwanda.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cThe Rwandan army doesn&#8217;t care whether you&#8217;re a Hutu from Rwanda or a Hutu from Congo, for them, it&#8217;s the same. This is the hatred that happened back in Rwanda imported in Congo [following the 1994 genocide]. I&#8217;m sure about what I&#8217;m saying because my father had many other friends who were Nandes [an ethnic group in the North Kivu region] that were living in Rutshuru who were not threatened or killed and who did not have to flee, but the Hutus were killed,\u201d said a Congolese Hutu man in Goma who was a survivor of Ethnic cleansing in DR Congo in the 1990s.<\/p>\n<p>Another string of violence against the Hutus was <a href=\"http:\/\/europe.newsweek.com\/ethnic-violence-dr-congo-kills-least-21-un-424649?rm=eu\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/europe.newsweek.com\/ethnic-violence-dr-congo-kills-least-21-un-424649?rm=eu', 'recorded');\">recorded<\/a> in August this year, when the Nande tribe targeted Hutu villages, killing 22 people, injuring 40, and burning down 70, in retaliation against the Hutus who were accused of killing tribesmen from the Nande tribe. These attacks were\u00a0carried out by two militia groups, the UPDI and the Nduma Defense of Congo (NDC), which are dominated by members of the Nande and Nyanga ethnic groups.<\/p>\n<p>The reason why the fights against these two communities of <a href=\"http:\/\/europe.newsweek.com\/ethnic-violence-dr-congo-kills-least-21-un-424649?rm=eu\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/europe.newsweek.com\/ethnic-violence-dr-congo-kills-least-21-un-424649?rm=eu', 'Hutus and Nandes ');\">Hutus and Nandes <\/a>are more dangerous than other tribal clashes is because they are both backed by \u00a0heavily armed militia groups\u2014the Hutus by the FDLR and the Nandes by traditional Mai Mai fighters, who are local militias, seeking to defend their communities from other armed groups supported by Rwandan forces, mainly through the recruitment of child soldiers.<\/p>\n<p>The rise of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-11456605\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-11456605', 'armed militia groups');\">armed militia groups<\/a> can be traced back to the 1990s. The\u00a0Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (AFDL) a Rwandan-backed group, was the first to take up arms in DR Congo followed by\u00a0several others, supported by Rwanda. Uganda also financed several others which made\u00a0dozens of local self-defence militias to emerge in the late 1990s, as a reaction to the foreign or foreign-backed groups, to defend local communities (Mai Mai fighters). Currently, there are more than <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-11456605\" onclick=\"__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'http:\/\/www.bbc.com\/news\/world-africa-11456605', '30 armed militias');\">30 armed militias<\/a> in eastern DR Congo and as long as they are present on Congolese soil, the civil war might be over on paper but will continue to plague the Congolese people\u00a0in reality.<\/p>\n<!-- Facebook Comments Plugin for WordPress: http:\/\/peadig.com\/wordpress-plugins\/facebook-comments\/ --><h3>Comments<\/h3><div class=\"fb-comments\" data-href=\"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/armed-militia-in-the-democractic-republic-of-congo\/\" data-numposts=\"5\" data-width=\"100%\" data-colorscheme=\"light\"><\/div>","permalink":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/armed-militia-in-the-democractic-republic-of-congo\/","short_url":"http:\/\/vnt.rs\/es2pm","share_links":[{"title":"Twitter","slug":"twitter","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?text=How%20armed%20militia%20groups%20are%20fueling%20genocide%20in%20the%20Democratic%20Republic%20of%20Congo%20-%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fes2pm"},{"title":"Email","slug":"email","target_attr":"","url":"mailto:?subject=How%20armed%20militia%20groups%20are%20fueling%20genocide%20in%20the%20Democratic%20Republic%20of%20Congo&body=VENTURES%20AFRICA%3A%20How%20armed%20militia%20groups%20are%20fueling%20genocide%20in%20the%20Democratic%20Republic%20of%20Congo%20%0A%0ARead%20more%3A%20http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fes2pm"},{"title":"Google+","slug":"googleplus","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/plus.google.com\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fes2pm"},{"title":"LinkedIn","slug":"linkedin","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/cws\/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fes2pm"},{"title":"Facebook","slug":"facebook","target_attr":"target=\"_blank\"","url":"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fvnt.rs%2Fes2pm"}]}],"TOP_STORIES":[{"url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/eko-atlantic-city-unveils-pearl-tower-first-residential-building\/","cat_slug":null,"cat_name":null,"title":"Eko Atlantic City to unveil Pearl Tower, its first residential building","img":{"src":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/download-Eko-320x220.jpg","srcset":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/download-Eko-320x220.jpg 320w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/download-Eko-640x441.jpg 640w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/download-Eko-768x529.jpg 768w, http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/download-Eko-1536x1058.jpg 1536w"}},{"url":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/these-three-nigerian-women-are-set-to-make-history-by-being-the-first-african-representatives-at-the-winter-olympic-games\/","cat_slug":"life","cat_name":"Life","title":"These three women are set to make history by being the first Nigerian representatives at the Winter Olympics","img":{"src":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Nigerian-Women-Bobsled-Team-Winter-Olympics-Ventures-Africa-320x200.jpg","srcset":"http:\/\/venturesafrica.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/11\/Nigerian-Women-Bobsled-Team-Winter-Olympics-Ventures-Africa-320x200.jpg 320w, htt